[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1883 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished third in the American Association with a record of 61–37, 5 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings came into the 1883 season looking to repeat as American Association Champions, as they had a league best record of 55–25 in 1882.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the team announced that catcher Pop Snyder would return as player-manager.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also made a big signing, as they signed Charley Jones, who played with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League from 1876–1878.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Jones had not played professional baseball since 1880, when he played for the Boston Red Caps of the NL, after which he was black-balled from professional baseball.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings also signed another former Reds player, John Reilly, who had also last played major league baseball for the Reds in the 1880 season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the diamond, the Red Stockings were led by Jones, who hit .294 with a team leading ten home runs, as well as a league leading 80 RBI.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Reilly hit a team high .311 with nine homers and 79 RBI.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Will White continued to be the ace of the pitching staff, posting a 43–22 record with 64 complete games and a 2.09 ERA in 577 innings pitched.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started off the season on the right foot, winning their first four games, and had an impressive 11–5 record in their first sixteen ballgames.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they were 3.5 games behind the Athletics.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would continue to play good baseball, and had a 31–23 record.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would then go on to win twelve of their next thirteen games to improve to 43–24.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they only moved up to third place.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would remain in third place for the rest of the season, finishing the year at 61–37, five games behind the Athletics.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1884 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished fifth in the American Association with a record of 68–41, 8 games behind the New York Metropolitans.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were looking to return to their 1882 form, when they won the American Association pennant before falling to third place in 1883.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club named pitcher Will White the player-manager for the 1884 season, taking over for catcher Pop Snyder.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season, although they did sign Tom Mansell, who had split the previous season between the Detroit Wolverines of the National League, and the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns of the AA, hitting .305 with 34 RBI and 45 runs between those two teams.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club also moved into American Park for the 1884 season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly was the offensive force on the team, hitting .339 with eleven home runs and 91 RBI, all club highs.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones hit .314 with seven home runs and 71 RBI, along with a team high 117 runs.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White led the way with a 34–18 record and a 3.32 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati got off to a slow start, as they lost their first game in their new ballpark, 10–9 to the Columbus Buckeyes, and they had a record of 4–5 in their first nine games, before reeling off four wins in a row to stay above the .500 level for the rest of the season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got red hot, as they eventually had a 28–14 record, only one game out of first place.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] In a three-game series against the Washington Nationals, the Red Stockings outscored their opposition 48–6.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started to fade as the season continued on, and with their record at 44–27 changed managers, bringing Pop Snyder back as player-manager.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati continued to slump, falling to 10½ games out of first place with a 52–35 record, but then won ten games in a row to climb back to within 4½ games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was too little too late though, as Cincinnati finished the season with a 68–41 record, good enough for fifth place, eight games behind the Metropolitans.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1885 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished second in the American Association, 16 games behind the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the Red Stockings hired O.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Caylor to become the manager of the team, the first time in club history that the club did not have a player-manager.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed Tony Mullane to a contract.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane, who spent the 1884 season with the Toledo Blue Stockings, had a 36–26 record with a 2.52 ERA in 67 starts, striking out 325 batters.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane was suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, as the Blue Stockings and the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons, another team he tried to sign with, folded after the 1884 season, and the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns attempted to reclaim Mullane, as he pitched there in 1883.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the Browns could reclaim him, he signed with the Red Stockings.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Frank Fennelly, who the Red Stockings acquired late in the 1884 season from the Washington Nationals, had a breakout season, hitting .273 with ten home runs and a league high 89 RBI.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones led the team with a .322 average, and had five home runs and 35 RBI to go along with it, while John Reilly hit .297 with five homers and 60 RBI.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Larry McKeon led the Red Stockings with 20 wins and a 2.86 ERA in 33 starts, while Will White had eighteen wins and a 3.53 ERA in 34 starts.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati began the season very well, putting up an impressive 16–8 record in their first 24 games to sit in second place in the league, two games behind the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then began to slump, as they would win only six of their next sixteen games to slip into third place, seven games behind the Browns.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On July 1, the Red Stockings acquired Jim Keenan and Larry McKeon, who both jumped from the Detroit Wolverines to join Cincinnati.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings improved with their new acquisitions in the lineup, as the team eventually moved back into second place, however, they were too far behind the Browns, and Cincinnati finished the season with a 63–49 record, good for second place, however, they were sixteen games out of first.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1886 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings finished in fifth place in the American Association, 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill had a breakout season, hitting .265 with five home runs and a team high 97 RBI, while Bid McPhee hit .268 with a team highs in home runs with eight, stolen bases with 40, and runs with 139.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Fred Lewis had a team high .318 batting average.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Mullane was the ace of the staff, as he had a 33–27 record with a 3.70 ERA in 56 starts, as he struck out 250 batters in 529.2 innings pitched.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were coming off a second-place finish in the 1885 season, which was their highest placing since winning the 1882 American Association pennant.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season; however, Tony Mullane, who had been suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, returned and made his Cincinnati debut in 1886.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings started the season off slowly, winning only four of their first twelve games to sit in seventh place.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would continue to play mediocre baseball, and would be in eighth place with a 24–35 record, 12.5 games out of first place.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a seven-game winning streak to climb into sixth place to bring their record to 31–35, however, they remained 12.5 games out of first.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team eventually broke over the .500 level, reaching a season best three games over .500 with a 50–47 record.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, Cincinnati faded down the stretch, and finished with a losing record for the first time in team history, as they were 65–73, which was good for fifth place 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1887 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished in second place in the American Association with a record of 81–45, 14 games behind the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Following a horrible 1886 season, in which the Red Stockings finished under .500 for the first time in team history, the team hired Gus Schmelz to become the new manager.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons of the National League in 1886 to a 43–79 record.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] He also managed the Columbus Buckeyes of the American Association in 1883, leading them to a 69–39 record and a second-place finish.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati signed George Tebeau to his first professional contract, and acquired Hugh Nicol from the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns in a trade with sent Jack Boyle and $350 to the Browns.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol hit .206 with 19 RBI and 38 stolen bases, as well as scoring 44 runs in 67 games in 1886.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly had a great season, as he hit .306 with a team high ten home runs and had 96 RBI, as well as 50 stolen bases.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill led the club with a .311 batting average, and his 97 RBI tied him with Frank Fennelly for the team high.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol led the American Association with 138 stolen bases.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Mike Smith emerged as the ace of the staff, as he had a 34–17 record and a league best 2.94 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Tony Mullane also had a solid season, as he had a 31–17 record with a 3.24 ERA in 48 starts.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got off to a fast start, winning their first five games, however, Cincinnati lost six of their next seven games to fall to 6–6.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a 21–22 record after 43 games, before winning nine of ten to rise up to third place with a 30–23 record.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] After going 3–6 in their next nine games, Cincinnati had a season-high ten-game winning streak.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they remained in third place, 8.5 games behind the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings continued to play good baseball for the remainder of the season, as they finished the year in second place with a record of 81–54, fourteen games behind the first-place Browns.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1938 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished fourth in the National League with a record of 82–68, 6 games behind the Chicago Cubs.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] During the off-season, Cincinnati hired Bill McKechnie to manage the club.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] McKechnie had extensive major league experience as a manager, as he most recently managed the Boston Bees from 1930 to 1937, leading the club to a 560–666 over eight seasons.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Cardinals from 1928 to 1929, leading the team to a 129–88 record and winning the 1928 National League pennant.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] McKechnie had his most success as manager with the Pittsburgh Pirates from 1922 to 1926, as he earned a 409–293 record.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] McKechnie managed the Pirates to the 1925 National League pennant, and won the 1925 World Series as Pittsburgh defeated the Washington Senators in seven games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] On October 4, 1937, the Reds released outfielder Kiki Cuyler following the 1937 season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Cuyler spent three seasons in Cincinnati, where he batted .293 with nine home runs, 128 RBI and 30 stolen bases in 323 games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds sold centerfielder Hub Walker to the Nashville Volunteers of the Southern Association on December 2.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] In 78 games with the Reds in 1937, Walker hit .249 with one home run and 19 RBI.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The next day, on December 3, the Reds were involved in a trade with the New York Yankees.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati sent shortstop Eddie Miller and $40,000 to New York for catcher Willard Hershberger.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Hershberger batted .325 with five home runs in 96 games with the Newark Bears of the International League during the 1937 season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Following the acquisition of Hershberger, the Reds sold catcher Gilly Campbell to the Montreal Royals of the International League three days later.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] On February 3, the Reds released pitcher Bill Hallahan.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Hallahan struggled to a 3–9 record with a 6.14 ERA in 21 games with the Reds during the 1937 season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The next day, on February 4, Cincinnati purchased second baseman Lonny Frey from the Chicago Cubs.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Frey hit .278 with one home run and 22 RBI in 78 games during his only season with Chicago.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Previously, Frey played with the Brooklyn Dodgers from 1933 to 1936, where in his best season in 1935, Frey hit .262 with 11 home runs and 77 RBI in 131 games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] In mid-April, the Reds signed pitcher Ray Benge as a free agent.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Benge did not play during the 1937 season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] In the 1936 season, he earned a record of 8–13 with a 5.49 ERA in 36 games while splitting the season between the Boston Bees and the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] In 1931, Benge enjoyed his best season, as he earned a 14–18 record with a 3.17 ERA in 38 games with the Phillies.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] On April 19, the Reds opened the 1938 season with a loss to the Chicago Cubs by a score of 8–7 in front of 34,148 fans at Crosley Field.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Ernie Lombardi went 3-for-3 for the Reds, while Billy Myers went 3-for-4, while driving in three runs.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds purchased pitcher Jim Weaver from the St.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Weaver had a 0–1 record with an ERA of 9.00 in one game with the Browns.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] In 1935 with the Pittsburgh Pirates, Weaver finished tied for the National League lead with four shutouts.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Following a 3–8 start of the season in their first 11 games, Cincinnati would win six of their next seven games, bringing their record to .500 at 9–9 through 18 games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds would stay hot throughout the month of May, as the club finished the month with a record of 15–9, which brought their overall win-loss record to 19–17 heading into June, as the club sat in fourth place in the National League.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] On June 6, the Reds acquired outfielder Wally Berger from the New York Giants in exchange for infielder Alex Kampouris.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Berger struggled with the Giants in 1938, hitting only .188 with four RBI in 16 games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Earlier in his career, Berger was one of the top sluggers in the National League.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] In 1930, he set the record for most home runs by a rookie with 38 when he played for the Boston Braves.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] In the 1933 season, Berger finished in third place in National League MVP voting after he hit .313 with 27 home runs and 106 RBI in 137 games with the Braves.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] In 1935, Berger led the National League with 34 home runs and 130 RBI.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Johnny Vander Meer became the only pitcher in major league history to pitch two consecutive no-hitters in 1938.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] On June 11, 1938, he no-hit the Boston Bees at Crosley Field.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Four nights later, in the first night game played at Ebbets Field, he no-hit the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] One of two balls that survives from this historic game is in the Seth Swirsky collection.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] After his double no-hit achievement, Reds' management wanted Vander Meer to change his uniform number to "00." He politely refused.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] On June 13, the Reds were involved in a blockbuster trade, as the team acquired pitcher Bucky Walters from the Philadelphia Phillies in exchange for catcher Spud Davis, pitcher Al Hollingsworth and $50,000.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Walters struggled to begin the 1938 season with the Phillies, posting a record of 4–8 with a 5.23 ERA in 12 starts, pitching 82.2 innings and nine complete games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati had a very solid record of 15–10 in the month of June, bringing their overall win-loss record to 35–27 by the end of the month, sitting in a second place tie with the Pittsburgh Pirates, only four games behind the pennant leading New York Giants.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds started off the month of July with a four-game losing streak, which dropped the team into fourth place in the National League and eight games behind the Giants.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati rebounded from this streak, winning their next seven games, however, the streaky Reds then dropped four games in a row following their winning streak.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Overall, Cincinnati had a 15–15 record during the month, as their overall record was 50–42 by the end of July, as they were in fourth place, 8.5 games out of first.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati put together a record of 18–14 during the month of August, bumping the club from fourth place into second by the end of the month with an overall record of 68–56, however, the Reds sat 6.5 games behind the pennant leading Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds were never able to catch New York for first place, as the team put together a record of 14–12 in their remaining 26 games, dropping the Reds to fourth place in the National League, as Cincinnati finished six games behind the pennant winning Chicago Cubs.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Offensively, outfield Ival Goodman led the club, as he hit .292 with a team leading 30 home runs, and drove in 92 runners in 145 games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Catcher Ernie Lombardi led Cincinnati with a .342 batting average, while he hit 19 home runs and had 95 RBI in 129 games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] First baseman Frank McCormick led the Reds with 109 RBI, as he hit .327 and had five home runs in 151 games played.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Outfielder Wally Berger, who the Reds acquired in a trade during the season, hit .306 with 16 home runs and 56 RBI in 99 games with the Reds.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds pitching staff was anchored by Paul Derringer, as he led the club with a 21–14 record and a 2.93 ERA in 41 games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Derringer led Cincinnati with 26 complete games, four shutouts, 307 innings pitched, and struck out 132 batters.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Johnny Vander Meer had an unforgettable season, throwing back-to-back no-hitters.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] He posted a record of 15–10 with a 3.12 ERA in 32 games.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Bucky Walters posted a record of 11–6 and an ERA of 3.69 in 168.1 innings pitched following his trade to Cincinnati during the season.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds 82–68 record in 1938 was a 26 win improvement over the 1937 season, in which the club finished in last place with a 56–98 record.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The 1938 season was the first time Cincinnati finished over .500 since the 1928 season, when the club finished 78–74.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds 82 victories was their highest total since the 1926 season, when the Reds finished 87–67.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati set a club record in attendance, as the team drew 706,756 fans, an improvement of 295,535 from 1937.
[src:1938-cincinnati-reds-season/1938-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds previously record high for attendance was in 1926 as the club drew 672,987 fans.
